e&gt;div]:border-border-400 [&amp;_.ignore-pre-bg&gt;div]:bg-transparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Great context! Here's my honest take:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>For someone going into AI security, the most impressive and relevant choice is actually the Reliability/Testing Harness</strong> — because AI security is fundamentally about making AI systems trustworthy, measurable, and resistant to bad outputs. A guardrails + evaluation system shows exactly that mindset. It also happens to be the easiest to explain and implement on top of PawPal+.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Here's what I'm picturing for your extended system:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>PawPal+ AI Advisor</strong> — you add a Claude-powered natural language layer on top of your existing scheduler. A user can type something like <em>"What should I do for my dog Max today?"</em> and the AI responds with care recommendations. Then your <strong>guardrail/reliability system</strong> validates those AI outputs — checking for harmful advice, low confidence, or nonsensical responses — and logs everything.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">This gives you:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">✅ <strong>Required AI feature:</strong> Reliability harness + guardrails (input validation, output checking, confidence scoring)</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">✅ <strong>Substantial new feature</strong> built into the existing app</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">✅ <strong>Easy to demo</strong> — you just type questions and show the guardrails catching bad inputs</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">✅ <strong>Security-relevant story</strong> — you're literally building a system that audits AI behavior</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">And it naturally unlocks <strong>2 stretch features</strong> within 4 hours:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The test harness (+2pts) comes almost for free alongside the guardrails</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Specialized prompting (+2pts) is just a few-shot system prompt</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>That's potentially 21 + 4 = 25/21 pts.</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Does this direction sound good to you? If yes, we'll move into step-by-step planning.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
